## Component Architecture

### Naming Conventions

| Type | Convention | Example |
|---|---|---|
| Component files | PascalCase | `ContactCard.tsx` |
| Hook files | camelCase prefixed with `use` | `useContacts.ts` |
| Utility files | camelCase | `formatDate.ts` |
| API service files | camelCase suffixed with `Api` | `ordersApi.ts` |

### Component Props

Always define explicit TypeScript interfaces for props:

```tsx
interface ContactCardProps {
  name: string;
  email: string;
  message: string;
  createdAt: string;
  className?: string;
}

export function ContactCard({ name, email, message, createdAt, className }: ContactCardProps) {
  return (
    <div className={`rounded-lg border border-gray-200 p-4 ${className ?? ''}`}>
      <p className="font-semibold text-gray-900">{name}</p>
      <p className="text-sm text-gray-500">{email}</p>
      <p className="mt-2 text-gray-700">{message}</p>
    </div>
  );
}
```

### Component Rules

- One component per file
- Export named components (avoid default exports for components)
- Keep components focused — split if a component does more than one thing
- UI components in `components/ui/` must be purely presentational (no API calls, no business logic)

